#VIRTUAL SURPLUS



Lightweight, dependency-free, responsive. Never before has financial capitalism so seamlessly resembled a software model- nor has open-source software been so deterministically user-friendly. 

Digital finance has peaked, but perhaps we've never been disillusioned by it. There's a common misconception among cryptoevangelists that digital currencies have somehow triggered a revolution in financial capitalism. But the technological shift isn't digital, it's virtual. The digital translates, it compresses. The virtual represents, it mirrors. 


#A CRYPTOAPOSTOLIC WET DREAM FOR VIRTUAL REVOLUTION

The particles.js plug-in creates particle environments that interface with browsers. As seen on venture-based blockchain platforms, the software functions as both brand identity and interface metaphor. In "The Interface Effect," Alexander Galloway discusses the complex relationship between technology and the visual systems that mediate it. "The history of the pixel is instructive in this capacity: at its invention in the middle twentieth century the electronic pixel was essentially the same thing as the binary bit, one existing in the modality of visible light and the other existing in the modality of mathematical value."

What's notable about particles.js isn't the mechanics of the plugin itself, but how the software operates as a visual allegory for the relativity of value. Particles attends to a palatable platform for the exchange of digital securities; a means by which the blockchain can be imagined as having risen from the crypt of the darknet into the cloud of the open-source. The particles easily dissolve into the slick copy of a FinTech landing page, a visual trope that's so ubiquitous it's virtually invisible. The gestalt effect is one of privacy and transparency, decentralization and invulnerability, accumulation and exchange. But the disillusionment lies in the allegory, not the aesthetic.  


