Nothing, and that’s precisely why it’s sustainable. Any economic system that lacks a material economic referent - such as gold - must 
rely on standardization, and in virtual finance, that standard is a system of protocols.


Virtualization is a modality of representation, whereas the digital is a modality of translation. 




In the beginning there will have been time. But first, a word about space: the vertical axis of signification. 

How do we imagine 
this means something, meaning--what kinds of representations do we ascribe to value? To time? How do we save time? Save it from what? From space? These 
questions are the stakes for what we understand as capital; space and time being the dual axis of its encryption. 

In talk about the economy, there's talk about crisis, there's talk about collapse. In one imagination, we have the decline of Empire; that is, of Imperialism, which is 
the disruption of the centers that hold the economic order in place, around which the periphery of the developing world gravitates. 
The other idea of collapse is the collapse of spacetime. Because the term "black hole" is also an economic term, describing a place where people or things, 
especially money, disappear without a trace. What's at stake in this second idea of collapse is the infinite, that is, the obsolescence of the very system of coordinates 
through which value itself can be measured. 





Virtual currencies, like any other technology, 
mirror the model of the hype-cycle. Hype cycles assign emergent technologies the historical development of a landscape: peaks, troughs, slopes, and plateaus. 
These are natural metaphors for space and time. Mapped on an axis this way, a singular technology is never one instance of a tool, but a continuous 
process of development. In other words, an economy. 


Capital is encryption. Value has always been mined.

Cryptograpy is a spatial determination. So is a bank. The financial crisis of the Late 2000's can be decoded 
as an ensemble of attempts to mine the banks, only to find that time had virtually been extracted in the form of debt, 
i.e., future time. 
Finance has been digitized for a long time, with the technology of the stock ticker being a 
sort of proto-digital technology. Mine, mining: does the value of gold emerge from storage or extraction?


